normalization_record.normalized_question_text:
Inelastic neutrino scattering in the quark model. Consider the scattering of neutrinos on free, massless quarks. We will simplify things and discuss only strangeness-conserving reactions, i.e. transitions only between the $u$ and $d$ quarks. Assume that inelastic $
u$ (or $ ar{
u}$)-nucleon cross sections are given by the sum of the cross sections for the four processes that have been listed above. Derive the quark model prediction for the ratio of the total cross section for antineutrino-nucleon scattering compared with neutrino-nucleon scattering, $\sigma^{ ar{
u} N} / \sigma^{
u N}$.

metadata.reasoning_chain:
For the reactions $
u d \rightarrow \mu^{-} u$ and $\bar{
u} \bar{d} \rightarrow \mu^{+} \bar{u}$ (Fig. 3.21) we have, similarly,
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\frac{d \sigma}{d \Omega}\left(
u d \rightarrow \mu^{-} u\right)_{\mathrm{cm}}=\frac{G_{F}^{2} S}{4 \pi^{2}} \cos ^{2} \theta_{c} 
\frac{d \sigma}{d \Omega}\left(\bar{
u} \bar{d} \rightarrow \mu^{+} \bar{u}\right)_{\mathrm{cm}}=\frac{G_{F}^{2} S}{4 \pi^{2}} \cos ^{2} \theta_{c}
\end{array}
$$

Integrating over the solid angle $\Omega$ we have
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\sigma_{1}=\sigma\left(
u d \rightarrow \mu^{-} u\right)_{c m}=\frac{G_{F}^{2} S}{\pi} \cos ^{2} \theta_{c} 
\sigma_{2}=\sigma\left(\bar{
u} u \rightarrow \mu^{+} d\right)_{c m}=\frac{1}{3} \frac{G_{F}^{2} S}{\pi} \cos ^{2} \theta_{c}
\end{array}
$$
Neutron and proton contain quarks $u d d$ and $u u d$ respectively. Hence
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\frac{\sigma(
u n)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} n)}=\frac{\sigma(
u u d d)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} u d d)}=\frac{2 \sigma(
u d)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} u)}=\frac{2}{\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)}=6 
\frac{\sigma(
u p)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} p)}=\frac{\sigma(
u u u d)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} u u d)}=\frac{\sigma(
u d)}{2 \sigma(\bar{
u} u)}=\frac{1}{2 \times \frac{1}{3}}=\frac{3}{2}
\end{array}
$$

If the target contains the same number of protons and neutrons,
$$
\frac{\sigma(
u N)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} N)}=\frac{\sigma(
u p)+\sigma(
u n)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} p)+\sigma(\bar{
u} n)}=\frac{\frac{3}{2} \sigma(\bar{
u} p)+\sigma(
u n)}{\sigma(\bar{
u} p)+\frac{1}{6} \sigma(
u n)}=\frac{\frac{3}{3}+3}{1+\frac{3}{6}}=3
$$
where we have used $\sigma(
u n)=3 \sigma(\bar{
u} p)$.

